<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-038-243 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 407 377</DOCID><JOURNAL>CSN  Oct 7 1991 n530 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The channels that time forgot. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Segal, Robert L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Vendors spend little time researching and planning before enteringa new market channel.andP;  Time-to-market issues are critical, butvendors must realize that proper preparation for distribution isessential.andP;  The channel planning process can take from one to fouryears.andP;  If a division is entering a channel with which themanufacturer's other divisions already work, approximately 12months of channel planning is necessary.andP;  Timely channel planningcan be accomplished by incorporating channel research into thephase review process, which is used by manufacturers to keepinformed of the product development's technical progress.andP;  Channelplanning begins with the identification of the end-user's supportneeds, buying patterns and financial conditions.andP;  Vendors thenneed to match the end user's buying patterns and supportrequirements with the reseller's sales process and supportcapabilities.andP;  The vendor also needs to find and hire resellers,set policies, develop contracts and terms and implement producttraining.andP;  The phase review process not only speeds up productintroduction, but also helps managers to understand a channel'sneeds.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Product developmentTime to MarketResearch and DevelopmentStrategic PlanningDistribution Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>